06.","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from any of various places, for example in Leicestershire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, and Yorkshire, all of which have the same origin as   Middleton  , with Old English <i>middel</i> replaced by its Old Norse equivalent <i>methal</i> after the Scandinavian settlement of northern and eastern England."],"variants":[{"name":"Middleton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places so called. In over thirty instances from many different areas, the name is from Old English <i>midel</i> ‘middle’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. However, Middleton on the Hill near Leominster in Herefordshire appears in Domesday Book as <i>Miceltune</i>, the first element clearly being Old English <i>micel</i> ‘large’, ‘great’ (see   Middlebrook  ). Middleton Baggot and Middleton Priors in Shropshire have early spellings that suggest <i>gem̄thhyll</i> (from <i>gem̄th</i> ‘confluence’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’) + <i>tūn</i> as the origin. This surname is also found in Scotland and Ireland.","History: A Scottish family of this name derives it from lands at Middleto(u)n near Kincardine. The Scottish physician Peter Middleton practiced in New York City after 1752 and was one of the founders of the medical school at King's College (now Columbia University) in 1767. One of the earliest of the Charleston, SC, Middleton family of prominent legislators was Arthur Middleton, born in Charleston in 1681. The name has also been established in Ireland since at least the 13th century; its presence was reinforced by settlers in the 17th century."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Melton was born in 1367, his father, William Richardus Melton, was 17 and his mother, Elizabeth Everingham, was 29. He married Lady Margaret Clifford in 1395, in Brough, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He was buried in Aston, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1367–":"1367–Surnud","1363–1455":"1363–1455","1367–Male":"1367–Surnud","1367–1442":"1367–1442","1398–1455":"1398–1455","1402–1452":"1402–1452","1350–1399":"1350–1399","1338–1369":"1338–1369","1338":"1338","1402":"1402","1369":"1369","1367":"1367","1455":"1455","1399":"1399","1398":"1398","1442":"1442","1452":"1452","1363":"1363","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","Longford, Derbyshire, England":"Longford, Derbyshire, England","Brough Castle, Westmoreland, England":"Brough, Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Aston, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Aston, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Melton Hall, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"1367–":"1367–Kuollut","1363–1455":"1363–1455","1367–Male":"1367–Kuollut","1367–1442":"1367–1442","1398–1455":"1398–1455","1402–1452":"1402–1452","1350–1399":"1350–1399","1338–1369":"1338–1369","1338":"1338","1402":"1402","1369":"1369","1367":"1367","1455":"1455","1399":"1399","1398":"1398","1442":"1442","1452":"1452","1363":"1363","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","Longford, Derbyshire, England":"Longford, Derbyshire, England","Brough Castle, Westmoreland, England":"Brough, Westmorland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Aston, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Aston, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Melton Hall, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England"},"fr":{"1367–":"1367–Décédé","1363–1455":"1363–1455","1367–Male":"1367–Décédé","1367–1442":"1367–1442","1398–1455":"1398–1455","1402–1452":"1402–1452","1350